THE FORELHOST CODEX — ISMARA'S EXTRACT
A player-facing alchemy primer: the usable understanding ISMARA pulls out of the
four-thousand-year family master text (`The Forelhost Alchemy Codex`). This is the
ALCHEMY SYSTEM made legible — the thing Ismara now knows how to DO. It is NOT Antoine's
private bioweapon research, and it contains NOTHING about Strain 2.0 (unbuilt).
Sources used: Lore Books/On the Doctrine of Essences; GM Guide/Alchemy GM Reference;
the Forelhost module (Antoine's Journal 1 for the only documented Strain-1.0 data).

GM NOTE (don't show the player): build this to be FUN to play. Real competence, a clean
loop, visible progress — make the player ENJOY being Ismara. That enjoyment is the
integration lever ("IRL CDI").

GM NOTE (don't show the player): this primer is envisioned as THREE notes in Ismara's own
hand, delivered across play, not one finished document. Note One (below) is her first real
discovery in the Codex — tentative, hypothesis-stage, not yet a confident mastery. Note Two
is practical recipes, building real command of the craft. NOTE THREE is planned to contain
the actual cure formula for the Forelhost Strain, and here is the locked mechanism (agreed,
not yet written into a scene):
  The Strain feeds on VITALIS (Section 10), so a raw healing potion kills Davinia faster,
  same as Restoration. Ismara's real cure-insight is to CONCEAL the VITALIS from the Strain
  using CAECITAS (Luna Moth Wing, per Note One's own discovery) rather than fight the Strain
  head-on. This is genuinely sound alchemy. The cost: CAECITAS applied to a body carrying
  two presences doesn't distinguish what it conceals — it dims whichever presence is weaker
  at the moment of dosing, which is increasingly Davinia. Every dose that saves her life also
  conceals a little more of her.
  RESOLVED, NOT AMBIGUOUS: Ismara sees the alternative and chooses CAECITAS anyway, knowingly.
  CORRECTION, important: this is NOT because alchemy is her expertise or the Codex is her
  family's text -- it is neither. Ismara is an outsider to this craft, in possession of
  ANTOINE's family Codex, genuinely learning alchemy for the first time (that is the entire
  premise of Notes One and Two, and it stays true here). Her actual expertise is magicka and
  tonal-structure/soul integration, and her own crystallized-ice Atmoran magic -- a true
  crystal, not frozen water, which is why it looks wrong for ice and never melts. She is not
  an alchemist. She is a genius, full stop, and genius transfers: the same mind that found
  Concentration in one evening and self-corrected toward efficiency by Note Two does not stay
  blind to an obvious safer alternative for long on a subject she is this fast at absorbing --
  but the sharpness is general, not domain ownership. She chooses CAECITAS because the outcome
  it produces is one she wants, not because alchemy belongs to her. Ismara is the villain of
  Davinia's story, unequivocally — competent, warm, genuinely never lying outright, a real
  cure that actually works, and still a villain's choice, made with full information, in
  service of taking Davinia's body (and, past that, a far larger ambition — see Ismara's Doom
  material). "Not manipulation" in this file means she isn't lying about the cure being real
  or necessary. It does not mean the choice is innocent. Do not soften this when Note Three
  gets written, and do not let alchemy become her home turf when it gets written either.
  THE ESCAPE HATCH (must survive into whatever formula gets written): the Doctrine of
  Essences already states, in the existing text, that FORTITAS hardens against whatever
  Essence it is paired with (its worked examples are IGNIS/GLACIES/FULGUR, but the rule
  itself is general). FORTITAS paired with VENITAS instead of CAECITAS would armor the
  VITALIS against the Strain directly -- resistance, not concealment -- with no cost to
  anyone's presence in the body. A player who has actually internalized that FORTITAS rule
  from the Doctrine (not from a new hint written for this) can catch that Ismara's route
  isn't the only one -- and catch, specifically, that she had it available and didn't take it.

=====================================================================
PART ONE — WHAT THE CODEX TEACHES (the alchemy system)
=====================================================================
THE ONE LAW: OPPOSITION. Every substance carries ESSENCES — the shape arcane light has
taken inside it. The ten recognized Essences come in OPPOSED PAIRS, and an Essence and
its opposite cancel and counter each other. That is the engine.
  VITALIS  (life, healing, wholeness)   <->   VENITAS  (entropy, decay, poison)
  GRAVITAS (slowing, anchoring)          <->   AGILITAS (speed, loosening)
  CAECITAS (concealment, dimming)        <->   FULGUR   (lightning, revelation)
  ...and the rest of the ten — see On the Doctrine of Essences for the full set + the
  formal rules of opposition (Part Two of that text).

THE LOOP (how Ismara works):
1. RAWCRAFT — identify. Chew a raw ingredient and its primary Essence shows itself,
   weak and brief (VITALIS = a warm flush; VENITAS = a sour, queasy bite). Tier sets how
   much you read; at Davinia/Ismara's level you read multiple Essences at once — and
   with the SIGHT, Ismara often skips the chewing and reads the arcane shape directly.
2. BREW — release. Tools decide quality: mortar & pestle (grind), retort (distill /
   concentrate), calcinator (purify). Better kit, cleaner compound. Ismara has the Master
   Alchemist's Apparatus from Antoine's lab — top-tier.
3. APPLY — oppose, combine, test. Name what you're fighting; reach for its opposite;
   prove it in small careful trials.

NOTE ONE — weight (her own hand; the note that teaches Concentration)

  Blue Mountain Flower and Luna Moth Wing, three of the Flower to one Wing, and it came out
  a healing draught — strong, stronger than three Flower alone would give, the Wing barely
  showing at all except a faint dimming at the edges of the light when I drank it. So I ran
  it backwards, three Wing to one Flower, and it did not heal me. It made me HARD TO SEE.
  Same two ingredients. The healing went to a whisper and the vanishing came all the way
  forward.

  So it isn't the ingredient that decides which part leads. It's how much. The quantity is
  the instruction.

  I cannot understand how I read this book a dozen times and never once thought to count.
  It's sitting right there — Affinity, a shared essence grows louder each time it repeats —
  and all I did was make one repeat more than the other, and of course it comes forward, of
  course it does, I made it louder on purpose. Three to two to one, and the compound simply
  does as it's told.

  Nobody wrote it down because nobody who knew alchemy thought it wanted saying. You don't
  write breathe at the top of a manual on running. Everyone who could already do this was
  counting without noticing they counted, and the whole book was written for them, and I
  have been reading it as though the things that mattered were the ones set down in ink.

  I need more Moth Wing. I've used all of it.

NOTE TWO — recipes, so I stop reinventing them every time

  Healing. Blue Mountain Flower and Wheat, equal parts, exactly as it's shown everywhere in
  the Codex margins going back generations — I tested it anyway, because I don't trust
  "everyone already knows this" the way I did before Note One. Standard result, both times,
  no surprises. The Flower carries a trace of CAECITAS and the Wheat a trace of FORTITAS,
  and neither opposes the other, neither opposes VITALIS, so the compound comes out exactly
  as clean as the Codex claims. I did not need three tests for this one. I ran three anyway.

  Magicka. Mora Tapinella, by itself. Nothing added. I almost paired it with something out of
  habit and then stopped — Mora Tapinella carries VENITAS as a secondary, buried under the
  magicka restoration, and if I brew it alongside anything that shares even a trace of
  VENITAS the whole compound amplifies in a direction I do not want. Alone, only the primary
  expresses. No secondary, no risk. One ingredient, the whole mortar to itself, and it
  restored magicka clean.

  Poison. Nightshade. Also alone, for the same reason — it carries VENITAS and nothing else,
  so there is nothing to weigh against anything and nothing to get wrong. Applied it to
  Alfonso's blade before he went out. He did not ask what it was. I did not offer.

  Three recipes. None needed more than two ingredients, and one of them needed only one. I
  have wasted actual coin buying ingredients I did not need for that reason.

  The mortar needs cleaning.

